                <head>372. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>President <persName corresp="#p_JLB1">Johnson</persName> signed into law H.R. 653
                    (P.L. 90–638; 82 Stat. 1359), on October 24, 1968. Section 2 established a
                    uniform tariff on reprocessed wool fabrics and blends based upon the chief
                    weight of the principal component of the fabric. The changes were scheduled to
                    take effect 60 days after enactment, and President <persName corresp="#p_JLB1"
                        >Johnson</persName> directed the U.S. Tariff Commission to study
                    alternatives. For text of the President’s statement, see <hi rend="italic"
                        >Public Papers of the Presidents of the United States: Lyndon <persName
                            corresp="#p_JLB1">B. Johnson</persName>, 1968–69</hi>, Book II, pages
                    1071–1072.</p>
                <p>The tariff changes were not well received in Europe. European Economic Community
                    representatives said that textile trade arrangements negotiated in <gloss
                        target="#t_GATT1">GATT</gloss> were imperiled. The Italian Government was
                    especially displeased since its textile trade with the United States was heavily
                    impacted by the changes. (Telegram 9916 from Brussels, October 15, and telegram
                    9131 from Rome, October 26; both in Department of State, Central Files,
                    INCO–WOOL 17 US)</p>
            </div>
